The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 Mumbai, Jan. 19: Market regulator Sebi today allowed exchanges to introduce currency futures on three more currencies  euro, pound and yen  pairing with the rupee. It is for the stock exchanges now to decide on their exact launch date. Earlier, currency futures were permitted only on the US dollar-rupee pair.                             
	 New York, Jan. 19: Citigroup has suffered a loss of $7.6 billion for the three months ended December 2009. Excluding the charges related to the repayment of bailout funds, Citi recorded a loss of $1.4 billion. In the year-ago period, Citi suffered a loss of $8.29 billion.                            
	 Tokyo, Jan. 19: Japan Airlines Corp has filed for bankruptcy protection. The airline, which owes more than $25 billion, has vowed to slash 15,700 jobs in an effort to survive in an industry hit by volatile fuel costs and fewer flyers.                            
	 New Delhi, Jan. 19: The coal ministry has asked the Bengal government to realign projects of Videocon, Bhushan Steel and Abhijit Group in Raniganj to ensure that they do not disturb coal reserves in the area.                            
	 New Delhi, Jan. 19: Ranbaxy will acquire Bangalore-based Biovel Lifesciences for an undisclosed amount. The proposed transaction will give Ranbaxy access to all of Biovels products, intellectual property know-how and manufacturing facility.                             
	 New Delhi, Jan. 19: Sony India plans to double the sales of compact digital cameras to 8 lakh units in 2010-11, besides launching 3D cameras. The firm sold around 4 lakh digital cameras last fiscal and expects to sell 5.5 lakh units by the end of this fiscal.                             
	 Mumbai, Jan. 19: The collection of Securities Transaction Tax (STT), a tax levied on transactions done on the stock exchanges, has witnessed a 25 per cent jump this year, chief income-tax commissioner R.K. Singh said.                                                                                                                          
